":["HD1298","HD1299","HD1300","HD1301","HD1302"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1887,"date_month":5,"date_day":25}],"cross_connections":[],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Frederick Howard Pierpont","first_name":"Frederick","last_name":"Pierpont","middle_name":"Howard","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Anticipated turbine engines used later in ocean liners","body":"Frederick Howard Pierpont built a working turbine model that his friends laughed at, so he got rid of it — and the turbine engine was later put into practical use on ocean liners. He always wished he had not given up the model. The independent prescience of a Connecticut toolmaker about marine propulsion captured the kind of unrecognized invention that small communities of his era frequently failed to encourage."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Old-time fiddler at kitchen dances since age fourteen","body":"Frederick played the fiddle from age fourteen onward — an 'old time fiddler' playing jigs and reels, who 'spent many hours making other people happy playing his fiddle at kitchen dances.' He also played mandolin. The kitchen-dance circuit was the late-nineteenth-century Connecticut working-class equivalent of community concerts; Frederick's name was on the local register of regular musicians."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Wife arrived alone from Ireland at seventeen","body":"Frederick's wife Mary Eleanor Elliott was born November 16, 1868 in County Cavan Ireland and arrived in America in 1885 at age seventeen, alone, on the steamship SS Circassia. She lived to age eighty-eight, dying May 9, 1957 in Waterbury Connecticut. The age-17 solo transatlantic Irish-immigrant arrival was a striking single-event biographical fact."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Roamed woods with sister testing medicinal herbs","body":"As a youth Frederick roamed the woods with his sister hunting for medicinal herbs — testing each plant to ensure it was not poisonous. The herbalist apprenticeship was part of his lifelong love of nature, hunting, and fishing. He was a member of First Methodist Church Waterbury where he lived his last forty-four years working as a toolmaker for John Draber Machine Co., Hendey Machine Plant, and Torrington Manufacturing Co."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"Litchfield 1862 birth to Waterbury 1934 death","body":"Frederick Howard Pierpont was born June 14, 1862 at the old Pierpont homestead in Litchfield Connecticut and died January 27, 1934 in Waterbury Connecticut at age seventy-one. Five sons: Edward Beach (1890-1958), Douglas Montgomery (1894-1973), Albert Howard (1896-1952), Ralph Andrew (1898-1971), and Frederick Elliott (1902-1972)."}],"slug":"frederick-pierpont-1862"},"HD1297":{"id":"HD1297","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"HD1293","mother_id":"X00402"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1864},"death":{"year":1938},"gender":"female","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X01471","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1}],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Helen Gertrude Pierpont Wilson","first_name":"Helen","last_name":"Wilson","maiden_name":"Pierpont","middle_name":"Gertrude","married_names":["Wilson"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"q